task.summary: Default task

Add gotcha around using greedy to find min no of numbers required to reach n -- it only works for fibonacci and is not a generic solution. Tried on perfect squares, does not work. Generic solution is BFS.

Solve medium return string with valid parenthesis after removing min no of unbalanced brackets using stack
Learnings -- Keep track of unbalanced brackets with their index. Reiterate the input string and add only those characters in the result whose index are not present in the unbalanced indices set.
Amend previous commit -- Add the actual file

Solve medium remove sub folders from a list of folder hierarchy by representing folders as trie and discarding the subfolders under a common folder
Learnings -- Folder hierarchy can be represented as trie.

Solve medium find minimum no of steps required to transform one word to another provided we can only replace one character in the word and the transformation should be valid ie. the transformed word should exist in the dictionary
Learning -- During my original implementation, I chickened out thinking that the implementation is too complex for this medium level of problem and I might be going in the wrong direction but I was wrong. Although it was a bit slow than pre-processing all the dictionary, it was still a valid solution.
If you are transforming a string by replacing some characters, instead of using substring to concatenate left and right part, get the charArray() and then replace the characters at the required indices directly. Cleaner to implement.

Solve easy check whether a string is palindrome or not after deleting at most one character
Learning -- Recursion is fun. Tried both options, in case of mismatch, ignore the begin character and check if remaining string is palindrome OR ignore the end character

Solve medium find whether two binary trees are flip equivalents i.e. if they can be made equivalent by flipping any node (swapping left and right pointer)
Learnings -- Got confused during implementation, still made it ! Every non null node has two options, either the children are flipped or not. Compare the children accordingly.
Update SymmetricTree with problem statement and simplify if/else

Solve medium KnightDialler problem, find total no of valid moves possible of required length in a dial pad
Learning -- As this problem asked for total no of moves, recursion was the way to go. Added memoization to fasten it up.
Thought of time complexity of the recursion problem with and without memoization, disadvantages of top down recursion.

Update comment in ContainsDuplicate3, very tricky problem
Tried checking the diff between the smallest and second smallest element, whether the diff lies within maxDiff but it does not work because maybe second smallest and third smallest elements diff were within range.
Hence the best thing would be to just iterate over all the input elements and check whether any element is present in window >= (current element - maxDiff)

Solve easy but tricky remove nodes whose values are outside a given range in the provided BST
Learnings -- I solved the problem on my own but it took time. In case of removal of nodes, it makes sense to directly recur in the appropriate half of subtree and return the first valid node

Solve medium find total no of ways to make total amount of sum if a coin can be used multiple amount of times using memoization and bottom up DP
Learnings -- Bottom up DP theory : If my current coin is 10 and I can reach 8 in 5 different ways, this enables me to reach 18 in +5 different ways too.

Solve medium change making problem, find min no of coins required to make sum using top-down and bottom up approach
Learnings -- Be careful when converting recursion to top down memoization and make sure that it's actually top down, during my initial implementation I implemented it wrong. I started from 0 till max amount, which led to incorrect results being stored in intermediate dp.
Although I solved up the bottom up DP quickly, top down DP became tricky.
Update problem statement in CoinChange2

Solve medium find total no of ways to reach end if their are obstacles in grid using bottom up DP
Learnings -- Trick was to correctly generate the base case of first row and first column and to reset the count if their is an obstacle.

Solve easy but tricky find whether a string is composed of repeated substrings by checking all the occurrences of the first character and generating substrings
Learning -- Initially I was thinking of checking substrings of length 2,3,4... and to see whether the input string length is a multiplier of substring length. If yes multiply the substring and check whether the expected string matches the input string. Then I thought it would be slow, but after solving it and moving on to discuss, realized that that was one of the most upvoted solutions. FML.

Solve medium and tricky problem, divide the current string into substrings such that there are no common characters in any substrings by reducing the problem to merge non-overlapping intervals
Learnings -- Be careful with list.add(index, value) vs list.set(index, value). Former one just adds the value at the index, it does not replace it.

Solve medium but tricky problem to implement LRU cache using HashMap and DoublyLinkedList using dummy head and tail node
Learnings -- 1. Dummy nodes are useful in all cases in which we need to add/remove elements from linked list 2. During my initial implementation I got stuck while implementing my own hashMap, I didn't think of the fact that I could use the inbuilt hashMap

Solve medium find min cost to delete characters to avoid repeating characters
The trick was to understand that we need to keep only the character with the maximum cost, rest all needs to be deleted.
Solve BinarySearch.io google easy find whether a tree is a subtree in another tree. Also any node of that tree can be optionally flipped. Very similar to FlipBinaryTrees of LeetCode.

Solved medium BinarySearch.io count no of ways to partition a binary tree such that both the partitions contains either 0's or 1's
Learning -- Partition problems have a pattern. First iterate the entire tree to get total no of 0's and 1's. Then do a postorder traversal and let parent node decide whether to cut edge of left/right subtree. Here the decision is made if the subtree contains all the 1's and no 0's and vice versa.

Solve medium jump game, find whether it's possible to reach the end from start provided we can hop to only specific indices.
Learning -- Was able to solve the problem in O(n^2) using simple bottom up DP. Linear way of solving would be to keep track of the maximum index reachable. If maximum index >= last index, we got ourselves a winner.

Solve easy word pattern, similar to finding whether two strings are isomorphic or not.
Learnings -- Use two hashmaps to keep track of source to target mapping and vice versa.

Solve easy find whether a string is rotated version of another string
Learnings -- contains() time complexity is not linear.

Solve medium compare two version numbers of the form 1.213.123.3 by comparing strings numerically. Care must be taken to remove leading zeroes before comparison.
Learning -- Removal of leading zeroes.
Solve medium find all disjoint group of friends by performing DFS from each friend and marking all the friends reachable as visited.

Solve easy find sum of all root to leaf binary path by storing the current path as base2 to avoid storing the path in a list.
Learnings -- Trick to avoid extra space was to directly store the current path as base2.

Solve medium check if a 'O' inner node is able to connect with a border 'O'. Trick was to do DFS from the border nodes instead of the inner nodes.
Learning -- In questions dealing with whether a list of source nodes can reach any target nodes, it's better to do DFS from target nodes and mark all reachable nodes.

Solve easy decode a run length encoded string by parsing string
Learnings -- Whenever a string has numbers in it and you are parsing it, remember that a number can have multiple digits. (During my initial implementation I forgot about it and got WA) A String can be converted into integer while traversing the string without storing the digits in a list
Add TODO to solve FriendGroups using UnionFind algorithm.

Solve easy find min steps to reach a target number if you can either double the input or increment it by 1
Learnings -- In case of problems dealing with find min no of steps to reach start from end, sometimes its prudent to traverse in reverse.

Solve easy check whether a matrix is valid toeplitz matrix or not i.e whether all the elements present in all the left diagonals are equal or not.
In my initial approach I did it by storing the leader of all the left diagonals. All the elements belonging to the same left diagonal has same value of (i-j).
But we don't need to go all this way, we can just iterate the matrix and compare the top left diagonal element during traversal.

Solve easy find all unique rotation groups of a set of strings by keeping track of unique rotation group and checking if current word is part of existing rotation group.
Learnings -- How to check rotations of a string.

Update solution for RectangleOverlap to include awice@ trick to find whether two line segments intersect.
awice@ is legend.

Solve find max product subarray by keeping track of the max prefix / suffix subarray product.
Learnings -- During my thought process of solving the problem, I incorrectly calculated that the max product subarray can be a middle subarray, otherwise I would have been on to something :( Trick was to understand that max product subarray can only start from the front or from the end. Take some examples of array with 1 -ve, 2 -ve and 3 -ve and you will understand why.

Solve medium find whether one string can be stretched to form another string, given that you can stretch a character for a min of 3 repetitions.
Learnings -- Create a Run length encoding of a string by comparing previous character with current character.

Finding max no of non overlapping subarrays with target sum == Find max no of non overlapping intervals
Use a greedy approach, fix first and check if another one can be added.

Solve find min length of two non overlapping subarray sum that equals target by considering subarrays from start (left) and from end (right). End result would be the min(left[i], right[i+1] for all 0 <= i < n
Learnings -- Dealing with non overlapping subarray problems

Update approach in finding shortest subarray that needs to be sorted to make the resultant array sorted.
Learnings -- In problems that requires finding a single subarray that does something, start from left and right and mark the initial boundary. Then check whether that boundary needs to be expanded further.

Solve medium but tricky/hard problem find shortest subarray that needs to be removed to make array sorted.
Learnings -- Need to find the longest increasing subarray present in the array by considering subarray that starts from 0 or starts at the end or is a combination of prefix of lis from start + suffix of lis from end.

Solve hard but medium problem insert an interval in an existing set of intervals such that the resultant intervals are non-overlapping
Learnings -- Reduced the problem to merge non-overlapping intervals by adding the interval to the existing intervals and sorting all of them. Non-optimal code but easy to implement.

Solve medium find longest word in dictionary that can be made from the input string by deleting some characters from input.
Learnings -- Check whether one string is a subsequence of another string.

Solve medium HouseRobber3 where each node in tree has two options, either it can be robbed or can't be.
Learnings -- In case of inclusion/exclusion question, care needs to be taken for the exclusion part. If a node can be excluded, the result of that would the max of if next node is excluded or next node is included. That's the trick. I forgot to consider that during my first implementation. Got WA. Fixed it quickly.

Solve medium find min no of steps required to reach a target state of the lock given that some states are banned by using BFS
Learnings -- Better to mark the node as visited before adding to the queue to avoid duplicates in the same level. Got TLE during my first implementation because of this mistake

Add another way of solving find maximum score after traversing two arrays by visualizing the problem as graph.
Learnings -- Where there are choices to be made visualize it as graph.

Solve medium find maximum sum of two non overlapping subarrays of L or M size, given that L sized subarray can occur before or after the M sized subarray
Learnings -- Leveraged the fact that the problem is asking for max non-overlapping sum which can be handled by tracking max subarray sum from left and right. Since the problem asked for specific sized subarray sum, need to calculate the sum by sliding window approach.

Update logic in find the length of the last word.
Learnings -- When problem statement deals with finding the last something, its sometimes better to iterate from the end.

Update approach in Generate unique bst that store values from 1 to n
Learnings -- In BST problems, try to leverage lower and upper bound during recursion.
